06629nam a22007215i 9780822390091DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223900917 a10.1515/97808223900912doi  a(DE-B1597)554033  a(OCoLC)1167420743  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJC261.D44 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a320.09222200aDerrida and the Time of the Political /cPheng Cheah, Suzanne Guerlac. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tpheng cheah and suzanne guerlac Introduction: Derrida and the Time of the Political -- tpart I. Openings -- tJacques Derrida: Co-Responding Voix You -- tpart II. The à-venir: Undoing Sovereignty and Teleology -- tEschatology versus Teleology: The Suspended Dialogue between Derrida and Althusser -- tThe Untimely Secret of Democracy -- tSovereign Stupidity and Autoimmunity -- tSovereign Hesitations -- tpart III. Responsibilities within and without Europe -- tEuropean Memories: Jan Pato˘cka and Jacques Derrida on Responsibility -- t''Call me Ishmael'' -- tAlgeria as an Archive -- tFine Risks, or, The Spirit of a Pacifism and Its Destiny -- tpart IV. Between Ethics and Politics -- tThe Aporia of Pure Giving and the Aim of Reciprocity: On Derrida's Given Time -- tPseudology: Derrida on Arendt and Lying in Politics -- tThe Fragility of the Pardon (Derrida and Ricoeur) -- tShould Democracy Come? Ethics and Politics in Derrida -- tpart v. Afterword -- tFinishing, Starting -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn intellectual event, Derrida and the Time of the Political marks the first time since Jacques Derrida's death in 2004 that leading scholars have come together to critically assess the philosopher's political and ethical writings. Skepticism about the import of deconstruction for political thought has been widespread among American critics since Derrida's work became widely available in English in the late 1970s. While Derrida expounded political and ethical themes from the late 1980s on, there has been relatively little Anglo-American analysis of that later work or its relation to the philosopher's entire corpus. Filling a critical gap, this volume provides multiple perspectives on the political turn in Derrida's work, showing how deconstruction bears on political theory and real-world politics. The contributors include distinguished scholars of deconstruction whose thinking developed in close proximity to Derrida's, as well as leading political theorists and philosophers who engage Derrida's thought from further afield.The volume opens with a substantial introduction in which Pheng Cheah and Suzanne Guerlac survey Derrida's entire corpus and position his later work in relation to it. The remaining essays address the concerns that arise out of Derrida's analysis of politics and the conditions of the political, such as the meaning and scope of democracy, the limits of sovereignty, the relationship between the ethical and the political, the nature of responsibility, the possibility for committed political action, the implications of deconstructive thought for non-Western politics, and the future of nationalism in an era of globalization and declining state sovereignty. The collection is framed by original contributions from Hélène Cixous and Judith Butler.Contributors. Étienne Balibar, Geoffrey Bennington, Wendy Brown, Judith Butler, Pheng Cheah, Hélène Cixous, Rodolphe Gasché, Suzanne Guerlac, Marcel Hénaff, Martin Jay, Anne Norton, Jacques Rancière, Soraya Tlatli, Satoshi Ukai  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title